<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Repair Torn Greenhouse Plastic</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Clean and dry the area thoroughly.</li>
    <li>Align the torn edges as closely as possible.</li>
    <li>Apply tape smoothly over the tear.</li>
    <li>Press firmly to ensure full adhesion.</li>
    <li>Apply a second layer on the opposite side if accessible.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Proper application improves both strength and longevity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When Tape Repairs Work Best</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Small to medium tears</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Early damage repair</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Areas with moderate stress</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Larger structural damage may require patching or replacement.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Applying Tape to Dirty Surfaces</h3>
  <p>
    Dirt and moisture reduce adhesion significantly.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Non-UV Tape</h3>
  <p>
    These repairs often fail quickly in sunlight.
  </p>

  <h3>Not Reinforcing Both Sides</h3>
  <p>
    Single-sided repairs are weaker.
  </p>

  <h3>Waiting Too Long to Repair</h3>
  <p>
    Tears expand quickly under stress.
  </p>
</section>

